hire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England","Irchester, Northamptonshire, England":"Irchester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1422–29 April 1485":"1422–29 April 1485","1422–1485":"1422–1485","1422–1486":"1422–1486","1442–1487":"1442–1487","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1400–Male":"1400–Deceased","1403–Female":"1403–Deceased","5 July 1475":"5 July 1475","May 1485":"May 1485","1403":"1403","1422":"1422","1444":"1444","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1487":"1487","1442":"1442","1475":"1475","1486":"1486","1485":"1485","29 April 1485":"29 April 1485","about 1421":"about 1421","Glassenbury, Kent, England":"Glassenbury, Kent, England","Bentley, Northamptonshire, England":"Northamptonshire, England","Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England":"Giggleswick, Yorkshire, England","Irchester, Northamptonshire, England":"Irchester, Northamptonshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Freeman","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>freman</i>, <i>fremon</i> ‘freeman, free-born man’ (Old English <i>frēomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), used also occasionally as a personal name. As an African American surname it was in many cases adopted as a name denoting a man freed of slavery. See also   Fryman   and   Free  .","Irish: Anglicized (‘translated’) form of Gaelic <b>Ó Saoraidhe</b> (see   Seery  ).","Americanized form of French <b>Lafrenière</b> (see   Lafreniere  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Freemon","meanings":["Variant of   Freeman  ."]},{"name":"Free","meanings":["English: nickname or status name from Middle English <i>fre</i> ‘free’ (Old English <i>frēo</i>), with reference to either tenurial status (‘free born’) or to character (‘noble, generous, open-handed’).","Irish: variant of   Freeman  .","Americanized form of Swiss German and German   Frei   and   Frey  ."]},{"name":"Fryman","meanings":["Americanized form of Swiss German <b>Frymann</b> or German <b>Freimann</b> (see   Freiman  ), and possibly also of the Dutch cognate <b>Vrijman</b>.","English: from Middle English <i>friman</i> ‘free-born man’ (Old English <i>frīomann</i>, <i>frīgmann</i>), symonymous with   Freeman   1."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":33,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Freeman was born in 1422, in Irchester, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Lawrence Freeman, was 23 and his mother, Mrs Lawrence Freeman, was 20. He had at least 2 sons with Joan Rudd. He died on 29 April 1485, in Irchester, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 63, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1422–29 April 1485":"1422–29. aprill 1485","1422–1485":"1422–1485","1422–1486":"1422–1486","1442–1487":"1442–1487","1444–1475":"1444–1475","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1403–Female":"1403–Surnud","5 July 147